Mohamed gave the right seeds answer for H3 – where you edit the 
&#39;crawler-beans.cxml&#39; file for your job, to pull seeds from a different 
place – but the situation is a little different in H1.14.

In Heritrix 1.14, it&#39;s assumed there&#39;s a &#39;seeds.txt&#39; file in your job 
directory. You can find and edit this file directly on the filesystem 
before you start your crawl. (When it&#39;s over a certain manageable size, 
the web UI will no longer show the in-page editable textarea.)

H3 is better at handling millions of seeds, but we&#39;ve done hundreds of 
thousands of seeds in H1 without problems.

Regarding your other questions:

(2)

For postprocessing analysis that pulls together a bunch of related 
resources (such as a text/html page and all scripts it inlines), you&#39;ll 
want to create a master index of what&#39;s spread across your files, then 
use that index to guide you to individual resources. Our &#39;Wayback&#39; 
project for browser access does this, as part of its operation, so you 
may want to look at it for ideas and code that&#39;s applicable to your use.

(3)

There&#39;s no master reference; our general recommendation is to start with 
the bundled defaults and tinker incrementally.

Many of the major alternative settings and components are discussed in 
the H1 user-manual 
(&lt;http://crawler.archive.org/articles/user_manual/index.html&gt;) or H3 
wiki user-manual 
(&lt;https://webarchive.jira.com/wiki/display/Heritrix/Heritrix+3.0+User+Guide&gt;). 
But others are discussed in other wiki pages, or old discussion threads, 
and to find and understand all the lesser-used options requires 
reviewing the Javadoc comments and raw source.

- Gordon @ IA

